	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64340349"><p><div class="quote"><p>And then... why is anyone using curl to do very specific SSL validation tests when tools like the openssl cli are available.</p></div><p>Because they are using curl for whatever reason they use curl (ease of its command line as compared to other https clients, or whatever).</p><p>
And it only makes sense to do the validation along with the rest of the https access (which could be the submission of a form, which contains sensitive data).</p><p>
The reason for this is twofold:</p><ol>
<li>convenience: why call 2 different utilities, when you could do all in one?</li><span class="substr"> </span><li>security: if middleman is smart, certificate could have changed between invocation of "validation" utility,</li></ol></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64340349">

